[5] Cholera - Guinea
Date: Thu, 18 May 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters Foundation [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/SODA-6PX77W?OpenDocument>

Cholera has killed at least 60 people in the south of Guinea in 2006.
Guinea, which remains poor despite its vast reserves of bauxite, the
mineral from which aluminium is extracted, was one of several West African
countries hit by an outbreak of cholera in 2005 that killed more than 800
people across the region.
"The cholera epidemic is still affecting Guinea, especially at Gueckedou
(in the south)," the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) said in a
report.
The report said 448 cases of cholera had been reported in Guinea between
the end of Jan and 23 Apr 2006. Of the 60 deaths recorded from the
waterborne disease so far, 47 had been registered at Gueckedou, near the
border with Liberia.
--
