[9] Cholera, Vibrio O139 - Taiwan
Date: 19 May 2006
From: Chan-Hsien Chiu, MD, MS <ihrfocalpoint@cdc.gov.tw>
Source: Taiwan's Center for Disease Control (CDC) [edited]

Taiwan's Center for Disease Control (CDC) herein notifies you that a native
cholera case in Taiwan was confirmed on 19 May 2006. This patient, a 58
year old female farmer, lives in Tainan County in southern Taiwan. The
causative agent was _Vibrio cholerae_ O139 confirmed by our reference
laboratory.
On 10 May, this patient developed severe watery diarrhea with vomiting
symptoms after she sprayed agricultural chemical products. She was sent to
an ER at a local hospital and was then admitted the next day. Due to the
onset of severe acidosis and acute renal failure, she was admitted to ICU
for dialysis and further treatment on 12 May. The next day, her diarrhea
was improved after receiving antibiotics. On 15 May, she was transferred to
a general ward and was discharged on 17 May. The stool culture, which was
collected at ER on 11 May, revealed _Vibrio cholerae_ after her discharge.
On the same day, the doctor reported her as a suspected case of _Vibrio
cholerae_ and the patient was readmitted to the same hospital for isolation
and further evaluation. Her specimens were sent to a reference laboratory
of Taiwan CDC for further testing. On 19 May, _Vibrio cholerae_ serogroup
O139 was identified.
After receiving the report from the hospital, Tainan County Department of
Health conducted an immediate investigation and put all exposed individuals
under investigations on 18 May. Due to the delayed diagnosis, there are 45
contacts including 29 health care workers. Rectal swab samples for all of
the contacts were collected and all of the results are pending. No
diarrheal illness has been identified from those persons in close contact
with the patient. To identify the source of the infectious agent, we have
taken the environmental specimens and food samples from her house.
Laboratory tests are being conducted on these specimens. Additionally, we
have conducted environmental disinfection in the patient's home.
Because this patient has had no recently travel history, she is confirmed
as the first native cholera case in Taiwan in 2006. Moreover, no contacts
have exhibited such symptoms one week after she got sick. Therefore, Taiwan
CDC considers that it is only a single sporadic case and unlikely to cause
spread of this disease in Taiwan.
--
Chan-Hsien Chiu, MD, MS
Director of Fifth Division (Disease Surveillance), IHR Focal Point
Center for Disease Control, Department of Health, TAIWAN, ROC
<ihrfocalpoint@cdc.gov.tw>
